{"news_desk": "Foreign", "print_page": "12", "section_name": "Health", "subsection_name": null, "byline": {"original": "By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr", "person": [{"middlename": "G.", "firstname": "Donald", "lastname": "McNEIL", "rank": 1, "role": "reported", "qualifier": "Jr", "organization": ""}]}, "abstract": "Failure of large-scale National Institutes of Health clinical trial aimed at preventing spread of HIV in Africa has led scientific community to reexamine how such trials should be conducted in poor countries; results show high percentage of women falsely claiming they took medication; main concerns are whether it is ethical to pay clinical trial participants, and whether results are scientifically trustworthy.", "type_of_material": "News", "word_count": "1170", "lead_paragraph": "Scientists are arguing about the extent to which it is ethical to pay participants, and whether results of trials that do so can be trusted.", "pub_date": "2015-02-05T00:00:00Z", "document_type": "article", "slideshow_credits": null, "headline": {"main": "A Failed Trial in Africa Raises Questions About How to Test H.I.V. Drugs", "print_headline": "A Failed Trial in Africa Raises Questions About How to Test H.I.V. Drugs"}, "snippet": "Scientists are arguing about the extent to which it is ethical to pay participants, and whether results of trials that do so can be trusted.", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"widewidth": "190", "wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-thumbWide.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 190, "subtype": "wide"}, {"height": 411, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "411", "xlarge": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-articleLarge.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 600, "subtype": "xlarge"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/02/05/science/05hiv/05hiv-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnailwidth